        "id": "intro_course_notes_-_hq-2020_ch7",
        "title": "Volunteer Opportunities with Sea Rescue",
        "content": "### Volunteer Opportunities with Sea Rescue\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: info@searescue.org.za\n\n#### 4.2 Pop-up Survival Swimming\n\nThe Pop-up Survival Swimming program is seeking volunteers to conduct Pop-up Survival Swimming courses nationwide. This opportunity is ideal for those who wish to volunteer for Sea Rescue within their communities at specific times without participating in rescue boat operations.\n\nIf you are interested in joining a Survival Swimming Squad to teach children how to control their breathing, orientate themselves in water, float, and propel themselves to safety in a controlled environment, please contact us. We will provide the necessary training, manuals, equipment, command and control structures, and guidance on when and where to teach.\n\n#### 4.3 Pink Rescue Buoys\n\nFor those who wish to be involved with Sea Rescue but prefer not to go to sea and have only a few hours a week to spare, consider volunteering to manage the Pink Rescue Buoys in your area. If this is something you can help with, please email andrew@searescue.org.za. These emergency flotation devices have saved 56 lives so far, and we need your help to relieve the pressure on sea-going volunteers by managing the Pink Buoys in your area.\n\n#### 4.4 Coastwatchers\n\nCoastwatchers are trained in NSRI operational rescue procedures and serve as the \"eyes-on-call\" to assist or even initiate a rescue operation. Typically operating from home with a clear view of the sea (or dam/lake), their exact location is marked on the station chart as a waypoint. Their role is to report any flare sightings, distress signals, or situations where persons or vessels appear to be in distress to the NSRI emergency number.\n\nThe Station Commander or Coxswain of the responding NSRI station may contact Coastwatchers to observe and report on targets to assist during an operation. Each Coastwatcher is equipped with a pelorus direction indicator, which allows them to take an accurate bearing of the target. This information is passed to the ops room, where the sighting is plotted as a line on the chart from the Coastwatcher's position along the reported bearing. As more reports come in, the plotted bearings converge, providing a good indication of the target's location.\n\nInformation from Coastwatchers is crucial in identifying where the casualty is and where it is not, aiding in resource planning and reducing costs associated with abortive calls, wasted response time, sea time, and distances covered.",
