        "id": "intro_course_notes_-_hq-2020_ch9",
        "title": "Donor Contributions and Financial Overview",
        "content": "### Donor Contributions and Financial Overview\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: info@searescue.org.za\n\n#### Donor of Time and Funds\n\nNot everyone can serve directly due to location, time, or work commitments. However, they can still contribute through funding or services, such as rescue base maintenance, servicing equipment, and other organizational needs. Donors can invoice for services and donate the money back, allowing for BEE certificate and Tax letter provision. Donations are tax-deductible under Section 18A status. Corporate donors can earn BBB-EE scorecard points under the SED category, as more than 75% of beneficiaries are \"per definition black.\"\n\n#### Funding and Financial Matters\n\nThe NSRI raises funds through public subscriptions and volunteer services. Its income mainly comes from donations by companies, individuals, and trusts, with a small government grant (less than 2% of annual income). The 2018/19 operating budget was R96m, with income sources as follows:\n\n- Individual Donations: 62%\n- Fundraising Activity: 1%\n- Membership: 1%\n- Legacies: 2%\n- Investments: 0.6%\n- Government Funding: 2%\n\nThe NSRI operates in a challenging economic environment, relying on philanthropy from donors, with limited government funding. It provides a public service valued at over R200m annually to South Africans and tourists at a low taxpayer cost, supported by nearly 60,000 donors. The only similar service is the South African Lifesaving services, which are limited in scope.\n\nOperational costs are affected by fuel prices and foreign exchange rates, particularly for fuel and imported engines. Boats are locally manufactured, with R24m invested in the local boat building economy in 2019. The organization recovers VAT but has no other tax relief.",
