        "id": "intro_course_notes_-_hq-2020_ch10",
        "title": "Rescue Operations and Crew Selection",
        "content": "### Rescue Operations and Crew Selection\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: info@searescue.org.za\n\n#### 6. Rescue Bases\n\nEach rescue base, often called a \u201cstation,\u201d is managed by a station commander, with support from a deputy station commander and a committee. These bases are established where there is a recognized need and a community of volunteers and supporters to facilitate their operation.\n\nThe committee is composed of senior station members, typically including the chief controller, station secretary/treasurer, station PRO, training/personnel officer, and appointed Coxswains.\n\nMonthly station committee meetings are generally followed by official crew meetings (business meetings) that allow all crewmembers to express their views and hear the ideas and opinions of others.\n\n#### 7. Selection of Crew\n\nThe Institute does not impose gender or racial restrictions in the selection or appointment of crew. However, the Organisation retains the right to appoint members based on acceptance criteria and their continued performance at the station as crew.\n\nNSRI crewmembers volunteer their services and do not receive payment or allowances. Crewmembers must indemnify NSRI against claims in the event of an accident.\n\nFor crewmembers under 18, parents or legal guardians must sign the indemnity. No one under 16 is allowed to join an NSRI station, and no one under 18 is permitted to participate in sea rescue operations.\n\nThe Station Commander has the final say on whether a Coxswain or crewperson may proceed to sea on active duty.\n\n##### 7.1 Insurance Policy\n\nThe NSRI has an insurance policy covering accidental injury or death for volunteers on duty or commuting to duty. \"Duty\" includes NSRI-related meetings, maintenance work parties, training, and rescue operations on land and in water.\n\nThe accidental death benefit is currently R1 million.\n\nThe policy covers up to R100,000 for medical treatment per volunteer per incident. It may also provide partial payouts for loss of earnings and disability, depending on the disability's nature.\n\nIf an injured person has their own medical cover, the NSRI\u2019s insurance will only activate once this cover is exhausted. If a volunteer depletes their personal medical aid benefits due to an \u201cinjury on NSRI duty\u201d claim and insufficient funds remain to cover further expenses, the NSRI\u2019s insurance will step in.",
