        "content": "### Medical and Insurance Requirements for NSRI Volunteers\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: info@searescue.org.za\n\nThe NSRI provides coverage for volunteers injured on duty. If a volunteer has a medical aid or hospital plan, the NSRI will supplement their fund to cover the maximum claim amount for injuries sustained during NSRI duty. For those without such plans, the Station Commander or duty coxswain must contact an Executive Director or the EOC for hospital admittance authorization. Private hospital treatment is covered up to R100,000, and additional costs at state hospitals are covered by the NSRI.\n\nTo ensure the safety and fitness of its crew, the NSRI requires all crewpersons to be medically and physically fit for rescue missions. Volunteers must undergo a medical examination upon joining and at regular intervals. This requirement is crucial for the safety of the crew and compliance with underwriter conditions. Insurance claims may be denied if the claimant lacks a valid medical certificate or is outside the acceptable age range.\n\nShore Crew, who are non-seagoing members, must also have an NSRI medical examination upon joining and every five years thereafter. The NSRI medical form includes a provision for color vision testing, particularly for the green and red spectrum. This is important for those who may wish to apply for a day/night Coxswain certificate, as SAMSA regulations preclude individuals with certain color vision deficiencies.",
