        "id": "intro_course_notes_-_hq-2020_ch12",
        "title": "Readiness to Serve",
        "content": "### Readiness to Serve\n\n![Effective Crewmember](images/Intro_Course_Notes_-_HQ-2020_p13_img2.png)\n\n- **Experience** includes maturity and judgment. This involves the courage to \"call it in\" or \"turn back,\" as well as the consideration and wisdom to weigh the potential \"reward\" of a rescue against the risk to the vessel and crew. It also means having the correct attitude and value system of a volunteer rescuer. Volunteers should support the aims and visions of the institute and be aware that they are part of something bigger than themselves.\n\n- **Skill** encompasses both theoretical knowledge and practical ability. The theoretical aspect is covered by well-designed, relevant, and engaging manuals and online training courses. Practical ability is achieved through extensive and \"value-for-time\" sea-going training activities.\n\n- **Fitness** is essential. If one cannot save themselves, they pose a risk to themselves and their fellow crew. The institute requires measures to prevent willing but unable volunteers from becoming a risk to themselves and the crew they serve with.\n\nBeyond these factors, personal commitment and family support are the two most essential elements for a successful volunteer.\n\n---",
