        "id": "intro_course_notes_-_hq-2020_ch13",
        "title": "Fitness and Training Requirements for Sea-Going Crew",
        "content": "### Fitness and Training Requirements for Sea-Going Crew\n\n**Contact Information:**\n- Web: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za)\n- Tel: 021 434 4011\n- Email: info@searescue.org.za\n\n#### 7.4 Fitness (Sea-Going Crew)\n\nAll new applicants must pass a fitness assessment before joining a rescue vessel. Current crew members are regularly evaluated to ensure they maintain these standards:\n\n- **Swim:** 200 meters in 10 minutes (2.5 minutes per 50m length in a pool). This is achievable for non-swimmers with training and effort. Must be completed without a lifejacket.\n  \n- **Tread Water:** 10 minutes. This can be done either wearing an NSRI wetsuit with hands on the head or without a wetsuit (hands can be placed anywhere). Must be performed without a lifejacket.\n  \n- **Water Exit:** Applicants must exit the water into their chosen class of vessel within one minute. No stepping on engine mounts or skegs is allowed. Fitted ladders may be used on vessels over 9 meters. A lifejacket and normal sea-going kit are required.\n\n#### 7.5 Age Requirements\n\nThe NSRI allows crew members aged 16 to 74 (up to 74 years and 365 days). Those older must self-insure and provide a specific letter stating this.\n\n#### 8. Training\n\nTraining occurs both ashore and at sea, but trainees are not allowed on rescue missions. The trainee period lasts a minimum of 6 months.\n\n- Trainees with proof of acceptable sea service on non-rescue vessels may count this time towards crew status, provided at least 20 hours are served on the largest vessel at their station.\n  \n- For service on multiple vessel classes, the required sea-time is: 20 hours for Class I and 30 hours for Class III; or 15 hours for Class II and 15 hours for Class III.\n  \n- The station commander may require additional hours for more practical experience before granting crew status.\n\nDespite prior sea-going experience, candidates must acclimate to NSRI protocols. Teamwork is crucial in rescue operations, and part of the training involves becoming familiar with the team. All sea-time must be documented on provided log sheets.\n\nNote: Sea-time as a trainee does not count towards qualifying sea-time for Coxswain certification by SAMSA.",
