        "id": "intro_course_notes_-_hq-2020_ch14",
        "title": "Responsibilities and Expectations of NSRI Station Crew Members",
        "content": "### Responsibilities and Expectations of NSRI Station Crew Members\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: info@searescue.org.za\n\nTraining is an ongoing function within the NSRI, and even after attaining full crew status, training continues. A Training Committee ensures that the highest training standards are met. The common purpose of all members is to save lives, making comprehensive training paramount.\n\n#### Expectations for Station Crew Members\n\nNSRI Rescue Stations are disciplined but not regimented. As a crew member, you are expected to conform to all station-specific and national requirements.\n\n- **At Sea**: The Coxswain's orders are law.\n- **Alcohol**: It is prohibited to carry or consume alcohol aboard any NSRI rescue craft or vessel, or when in uniform.\n- **Public Perception**: The public judges our conduct and appearance, often holding us in high esteem.\n- **Maintenance and Cleaning**: Alongside the excitement of sea rescues, regular maintenance and cleaning routines are essential.\n- **Attitude**: Enthusiasm and self-motivation are crucial.\n\n#### Confidentiality\n\nDuring NSRI duties, you may encounter confidential information. It is crucial not to divulge details of operations to the media or others, nor should you express personal opinions on operations. Media inquiries should be directed to the station commander or media liaison officer (082 3803800).\n\n#### Duty\n\nThe duty period typically lasts one week, depending on station policies, with off-duty periods varying based on crew numbers. During duty, crew members must respond to SMS or WhatsApp call-out systems, ensuring they are fit and ready for duty at any time during the week. The duty crew also practices at sea and performs maintenance work on the station during their duty week.",
