        "id": "intro_course_notes_-_hq-2020_ch15",
        "title": "NSRI Uniform and Volunteer Expectations",
        "content": "### NSRI Uniform and Volunteer Expectations\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: info@searescue.org.za\n\nThe NSRI uniform should be worn during training and when on duty. Life jackets and protective clothing such as wet suits and helmets are provided by the Institute.\n\nNSRI is a voluntary organisation and there is no monetary reward for services rendered. Some of the rewards you can look forward to include the satisfaction of undertaking vital work of a humanitarian nature, and the enjoyment of esprit de corps and the camaraderie of your fellow crewmembers. You can expect to be called out on search and rescue missions in both fair and foul weather and to submit, in some instances, to considerable physical discomfort during these missions.\n\nYou can expect to spend more than just one Saturday and one Sunday a month at the station maintenance sessions. Crew are expected to respond cheerfully to extra calls being made on them in respect of time and effort as the occasion warrants.\n\n### The Rescue Fleet\n\n#### 10.1 Class 1 Vessels\n\n![A Class 1 vessels](images/Intro_Course_Notes_-_HQ-2020_p16_img2.jpeg)",
