        "content": "### Rescue Vessels Overview\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: info@searescue.org.za\n\nThese craft vary between 10 to 14 metres in length and carry a crew between four to six persons. They are fitted with a cabin and are capable of staying at sea for up to two days. They have inboard diesel engines.\n\n#### Class 2 and 3 Vessels\n\n![Class 2 and 3 vessels](images/Intro_Course_Notes_-_HQ-2020_p17_img2.jpeg)\n\nThese are high-speed twin-engine inshore rescue vessels, which include 5.5m, 6.5m, 7.3m, 8.5m, 8.8m, and 10m in length vessels, capable of speeds of up to 35 knots. They are RIBs (Rigid Inflatable Boats) and have the advantage that they may be moved on road trailers to a suitable launching site near the scene of the incident. They have outboard petrol engines. Those equipped with Radar are designated as Class 2 vessels. The fleet is in the process of being standardised so that it will consist mainly of 6.5m, 8.8m, and 10m RIBs.",
