        "id": "pre-sea_training_course_notes_ch5",
        "title": "Boating Terminology and Voyage Preparation",
        "content": "### Boating Terminology and Voyage Preparation\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: [bretta@searescue.org.za](mailto:bretta@searescue.org.za)\n\n#### Key Terms\n\n- **Propeller**: A device rotated by the motor to propel the vessel through the water.\n- **Safety Equipment**: The equipment to be carried for the safe navigation of the boat, and/or for use in the event of an emergency.\n- **Scupper**: Openings in the bulwarks for the purpose of draining water off the deck.\n- **Skipper**: The person in sole charge of the vessel and crew (coxswain in NSRI).\n- **Sponsons**: Inflatable tubes forming the sides of an inflatable boat (pontoons).\n- **Starboard**: Right-hand side of the boat when looking ahead.\n- **Stern**: The rear part of the vessel. Also referred to as \u201caft\u201d or \u201cafter end\u201d.\n- **Transom**: Flat upright section of the stern upon which the motor(s) are mounted.\n- **Waterline**: This is the line where the surface of water reaches the side of the hull.\n\n#### Voyage Details\n\nIt is extremely important to leave your personal details and a contact number of immediate family members at the boat station you are leaving from. Leave voyage details with a family member, launch site office, local NSRI station, or your colleagues staying on shore.\n\nDetails should include the following:\n\n- Boat name, colour, registration number and radio call sign.\n- Skipper's Name, ID number.\n- Names of all persons on board.\n- Intended time of return.",
