        "id": "pre-sea_training_course_notes_ch11",
        "title": "Firefighting Principles on Vessels",
        "content": "### Firefighting Principles on Vessels\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: [bretta@searescue.org.za](mailto:bretta@searescue.org.za)\n\nRemove one or more and combustion will cease. This is the principle of firefighting.\n\n![The Triangle of Combustion](images/Pre-sea_Training_Course_Notes_p12_img2.jpeg)\n\nOn very small vessels, the first line of defence will be the fire-extinguisher. On the larger boats, water pumps will enable fire hoses to be used.\n\nRemember, however, that water must never be sprayed on a liquid fuel fire as it could result in spreading the fire. The only exception is if a very fine mist spray is produced with a high water pressure nozzle.\n\nAlso note that it will be difficult to extinguish a fire that is being fed with a supply of fuel. To isolate any possible flow of fuel out of the tanks, fuel shut-off valves are fitted to fuel tanks. Provision is made to operate them remotely.\n\nOn the larger vessels with engine rooms, means are provided to shut off all vents that supply air to the engine room should this be the seat of the fire. On such vessels, a fixed fire extinguishing system is also fitted to administer a smothering gas such as CO2.",
