        "id": "pre-sea_training_course_notes_ch12",
        "title": "Fire Extinguishers",
        "content": "### Fire Extinguishers\n\n#### Colour Coding\n\nAccording to the latest South African Bureau of Standards (SABS) code, all fire extinguishers must be red, with the type of extinguisher distinguished by the label colour. The label should include the following essential information:\n\n1. The classes of fires for which it has been designed.\n2. The content of the extinguisher.\n3. The controlling method (operating instructions).\n\nThe extinguisher should also have a service label indicating:\n\n1. The date of service.\n2. The name of the technician.\n3. The serial number of the technician.\n\nRegulations require one 1.5kg dry powder extinguisher per motor. On larger vessels with multiple compartments, there should be one extinguisher in each compartment. Fire extinguishers must be serviced annually by a SAMSA accredited (Dotfas) dealer. Small fire extinguishers have an average discharge time of only about 20 seconds, so it is important to direct the jet of the extinguisher close to the base of the fire.\n\n#### Immediate Steps in the Event of a Fire\n\n- Turn the vessel so that smoke blows away, downwind, and clear of the vessel.\n- Stop the engine and disconnect the fuel lines or operate remote fuel shut-off valves.\n- Direct the fire extinguisher discharge at the base of the flame or smother with wet clothing.\n- If in the engine room, close all vents and operate the gas smothering valves.\n\n![Fire Extinguisher](images/Pre-sea_Training_Course_Notes_p1_img1.jpeg)",
