        "title": "Fire Extinguishers: CO2 and Dry Powder",
        "content": "### Fire Extinguishers: CO2 and Dry Powder\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: [bretta@searescue.org.za](mailto:bretta@searescue.org.za)\n\n#### CO2 Extinguisher\n\n1. Due to the thick steel cylinder required to contain the pressure of 0.53 bar, the extinguisher is expensive.\n2. CO2 has a very short \u201cthrow\u201d and the operator has to be close to the fire, which may be impossible in the case of very hot fires.\n3. Could be detrimental to very delicate equipment.\n\n#### Dry Powder Extinguisher (Dry Chemical Powder or DCP) \u2013 Blue Label\n\n![Dry powder based extinguisher](images/Pre-sea_Training_Course_Notes_p17_img2.jpeg)\n\n- Can be used on virtually all classes of fires. The \u201call purpose\u201d dry powder is better in extinguishing fires than \u201cstandard\u201d powder and is much better in preventing flash-back of fires. However, it is more expensive.\n\n**Advantages:**\n\n1. Is effective on most classes of fire (especially the all-purpose powder).\n2. Powder has a long throw and acts as a protective shield against the heat.\n3. Emission of the powder can be controlled for approximately half an hour after first operating the extinguisher.\n4. The 4.5 kg extinguisher is light enough for a slightly built person to use.",
