        "id": "pre-sea_training_course_notes_ch19",
        "title": "Hypothermia Prevention and HELP Position",
        "content": "### Hypothermia Prevention and HELP Position\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: [bretta@searescue.org.za](mailto:bretta@searescue.org.za)\n\n#### Techniques for Preventing Hypothermia\n\n- **Getting out of the wind.**\n- **Replacing wet clothes with dry clothes or blankets.**\n- **No alcohol.**\n- **Giving hot liquids by mouth if the person can drink it themselves.**\n- **Assuming the HELP or huddle positions.**\n\n#### In the Water\n\n##### The HELP Position\n\nThe Heat Escape Lessening Position (HELP) is crucial for minimizing heat loss and slowing down hypothermia while in the water. This position reduces water flow around the body and delays the onset of hypothermia. \n\n- **Foetal Position:** Protects areas where heat is lost quickly, such as where arteries are close to the skin.\n- **Crossed Legs and Arms:** Bring legs close to the chest and hold knees with interlocked fingers to prevent losing grip as hypothermia sets in.\n- **Balance:** Maintain balance by pushing the head backwards.\n\nTo effectively maintain this position, a life jacket must be worn and properly donned.\n\n![HELP Position](images/Pre-sea_Training_Course_Notes_p1_img1.jpeg)",
