        "id": "pre-sea_training_course_notes_ch22",
        "title": "Initial Assessment and Emergency Protocols",
        "content": "### Initial Assessment and Emergency Protocols\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: [bretta@searescue.org.za](mailto:bretta@searescue.org.za)\n\n#### 8.2 The Initial Assessment of an Injured Person\n\nThe aim of the initial assessment is to identify life-threatening problems and resolve them immediately.\n\n- **Stop Visible Bleeding**: Identify and stop visible bleeding by applying direct pressure.\n- **Check Circulation**: Observe the patient\u2019s color and check for signs of blood circulation (awake and responding or breathing well). If there is no circulation, the face and lips will turn blue.\n- **Chest Compressions**: If there is no sign of life (unconscious, pale, immobile, not breathing), begin chest compressions. Press hard and fast in the center of the chest on the nipple line.\n- **Recovery Position**: If the ill or injured person is unconscious but breathing well, turn them over on their side into the recovery position.\n- **First Aid/Emergency Care**: Provide other necessary first aid or emergency care.\n\n#### 9 Alcohol and Drugs\n\n- Alcohol or drugs shall not be taken aboard a vessel.\n- Crew found under the influence must be taken back to shore and disembarked.\n- Such persons pose a danger to themselves, the crew, and the vessel's safety.\n- A skipper under the influence can expect harsh legal consequences, especially if an accident occurs.\n\n#### 10 Collision, Grounding, Fire, and Capsize\n\nIt is difficult to establish hard and fast rules for emergencies such as collisions, groundings, and fires. However, priorities must be established when an emergency situation occurs, and this section provides some broad guidelines.\n\n---",
