        "id": "pre-sea_training_course_notes_ch24",
        "title": "Emergency Procedures for Collisions and Grounding",
        "content": "### Emergency Procedures for Collisions and Grounding\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: [bretta@searescue.org.za](mailto:bretta@searescue.org.za)\n\n#### Collision Procedures\n\n14. Use the radio to call for assistance.  \n15. Obtain particulars of the other vessel, including the name of the vessel, port of registry, name of master, destination, and nature of damage sustained.  \n16. Ensure that all details are well documented in the logbook and that the position of the collision is plotted on the chart.\n\n#### Grounding Procedures\n\n1. Account for all persons aboard.  \n2. Ascertain if anyone has been injured, and if necessary, remove them to a place of safety and attend to injuries. Close and secure all watertight doors and hatches.  \n3. Prepare lifesaving equipment and don life jackets.  \n4. Carry out damage assessment.  \n5. If aground on a shelving bottom and the vessel is being pushed further ashore (especially on a rising tide), drop anchor to keep the bow into the surf and reduce the rate of onshore drift.  \n6. Check for ingress of water and start pumps if necessary.  \n7. If the vessel is aground on an obstruction, check the surroundings to ascertain where she is being \"held.\" Do not force the vessel off the obstruction with the motors, as this may exacerbate damage or start a leak. On a rising tide, it may be possible to get her off without further damage by trimming the vessel.  \n8. Call for assistance.  \n9. Check fuel tanks for damage and isolate if necessary to prevent contaminated fuel from being fed to the engines.",
