        "id": "trainee_crew_module_1_ch18",
        "title": "Rescue Base Operations and Maintenance",
        "content": "### Rescue Base Operations and Maintenance\n\nWeb: [www.searescue.org.za](http://www.searescue.org.za) | Tel: 021 434 4011 | Email: [bretta@searescue.org.za](mailto:bretta@searescue.org.za)\n\n#### Emergency Signals\n\n- Slowly and repeatedly raising and lowering arms outstretched to each side.\n- The radiotelegraph alarm signal.\n- The radiotelephone signal.\n- Signals transmitted by emergency position-indicating radio beacons.\n- Approved signals transmitted by radio communication systems (i.e., GMDSS).\n\n#### Rescue Bases\n\nCrew members have responsibilities not only towards the rescue boats but also to the station. Station fittings and equipment require regular maintenance and cleaning, along with the vehicle and boat trailers. Major items such as shed doors, boat cradle, winch, and winch wires will require regular lubrication, and there will be many smaller items that will need lubrication and protection from the corrosive maritime environment in which they are located.\n\nYou should familiarize yourself with the following:\n\n- **Security**: Know where keys are kept, the locking up procedure, and if there is an alarm system.\n- **Firefighting Equipment**: Be aware of where the fire extinguishers are situated and the types of fires they can be used on, including fire hoses, fire mains, and axes.\n- **Electrical Systems**: Understand the main electrical distribution board and the various circuits supplying the base.\n- **Water Supply**: Know the position of the main stopcock.\n- **Equipment Storage**: Be aware of where various items of equipment/tools are stored.\n- **Flammable Items**: Know where flammable items such as fuel, oils, paints, and cleaning materials are stowed and disposed of.\n- **Authorized Equipment Use**: Do not operate or attempt to operate any equipment that you are not authorized to operate (e.g., winches, tractors, vehicles).\n- **SOPs and Checklists**: Study the Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) and checklists. The process of doing the checklists makes you familiar with the location of all the equipment, so that even when you are out on a dark, rough night at sea, you know instinctively where the equipment is and how to use it.",
